06410nam a22009855i 9780813553368DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2011023491  a97808135533687 a10.36019/97808135533682doi  a(DE-B1597)530418  a(OCoLC)781542953  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aGN289b.G463 2012 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a611/.018166322300aGenetics and the Unsettled Past :bThe Collision of DNA, Race, and History /ced. by Keith Wailoo, Alondra Nelson, Catherine Lee. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (370 p.) :b2 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRutgers Studies on Race and Ethnicity0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOur genetic markers have come to be regarded as portals to the past. Analysis of these markers is increasingly used to tell the story of human migration; to investigate and judge issues of social membership and kinship; to rewrite history and collective memory; to right past wrongs and to arbitrate legal claims and human rights controversies; and to open new thinking about health and well-being. At the same time, in many societies genetic evidence is being called upon to perform a kind of racially charged cultural work: to repair the racial past and to transform scholarly and popular opinion about the “nature” of identity in the present. Genetics and the Unsettled Past considers the alignment of genetic science with commercial genealogy, with legal and forensic developments, and with pharmaceutical innovation to examine how these trends lend renewed authority to biological understandings of race and history. This unique collection brings together scholars from a wide range of disciplines—biology, history, cultural studies, law, medicine, anthropology, ethnic studies, sociology—to explore the emerging and often contested connections among race, DNA, and history. Written for a general audience, the book’s essays touch upon a variety of topics, including the rise and implications of DNA in genealogy, law, and other fields; the cultural and political uses and misuses of genetic information; the way in which DNA testing is reshaping understandings of group identity for French Canadians, Native Americans, South Africans, and many others within and across cultural and national boundaries; and the sweeping implications of genetics for society today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEthnicity. 0aGene mapping. 0aGenetic markers. 0aGenomics. 0aHuman population genetics. 0aRace. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbram, Gabriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAronson, Jay D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun, Lundy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChow-White, Peter A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Reanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFujimura, Joan H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Jennifer A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammonds, Evelynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinterberger, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacob, Michelle M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohli-Laven, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a